(
	{
		Title = "What is IRC?";
		Content = "<p>IRC stands for Internet Relay Chat and was created in 1988. IRC is a way for people to talk to each other online. It allows for group conferencing with many users, as well as private messaging between two users. There are over a thousand IRC networks to chat on, with hundreds of thousands of channels covering thousands of chat topics.</p>";
	},
	Space,
	{
		Title = "Direct IRC Connections";
		Content = "<p>With Colloquy, a direct IRC connection is a communication channel between your mobile device and the chat server that you are connected to. The alternative to a direct IRC connection is to use a bouncer.</p>";
		SectionHeader = "Getting Connected & Setup";
	},
	{
		Title = "Colloquy Bouncers";
		Content = "<p>In IRC terms, a bouncer is a piece of software that sits between you and the IRC server that you are connected to. This allows you to do a number of things, including connecting to the same room from multiple locations and stay connected to IRC when Colloquy has been closed.</p>\n<p>Due to the usefulness IRC bouncers, we have built a bouncer into Colloquy for Mac OS X. In addition to being a normal bouncer, the Colloquy bouncer also generates Push Notifications that are sent to your device and syncs connections over from your Mac to the mobile version of Colloquy on your device.</p>\n<p>There are two parts to setting up Colloquy\U2019s bouncer; setting up Colloquy on you Mac and setting up Colloquy on your device:</p>\n<ol><li>On your Mac, the first thing you\U2019ll need to do is install the latest version of Colloquy that has the bouncer built-in. After that, open Colloquy\U2019s preferences and open the Bouncer panel. Fill out the appropriate fields as necessary and write the values down if you need to. Although Colloquy will attempt to forward ports automatically with your router, this sometimes might not work. You can check to make sure the port is forwarded at <u>CanYouSeeMe.org</u>. If the port is not forwarded, you can consult <u>PortForward.com</u> for details on how to forward ports in your router.</li>\n<li>On your device, open Colloquy and go to the Connections tab and tap the \U201c+\U201d button in the top-left corner and select \U201cColloquy Bouncer\U201d from the menu. Fill out the fields as necessary. The \U201cAddress\U201d should have the IP address or host-name of your Mac running Colloquy. You can find this out by visiting <u>colloquy.info/&#8203;ip.php</u> on your Mac. Tap \U201cConnect\U201d in the top-right corner once the fields are filled out, and if all went well, your device will connect to your Mac and download a list of IRC connections.</p>\n<p><em>Note: If you could not connect, it means there is something preventing the connection. Check to make sure your firewall isn\U2019t blocking incoming or outgoing traffic from Colloquy and that the port is open.</em></p>";
	},
	{
		Title = "Finding Places to Talk";
		Content = "<p>There are over a thousand networks and hundreds of thousands of chat rooms on IRC. Colloquy conveniently provides a list of around 25 top networks that you can join and chat on. You can find this list by tapping the \U201c+\U201d button on the Connections tab, creating an IRC Connection and tapping the blue-arrow button in the \U201cAddress\U201d field.</p>\n<p>Once you picked a network to talk on \U2014 if you can't decide, pick one at random \U2014 tap \U201cConnect\U201d in the top-right corner. Now you need to find a room to talk in, so go to the Colloquies tab, tap the \U201c+\U201d button and select \U201cJoin a Chat Room\U201d. Then tap the blue-arrow button in the \U201cName\U201d field. If you have a specific topic you want to find, you can search for it. Otherwise, scroll down until you find a room to chat that interests you \U2014 and have fun!</p>\n<p>If you would like to search for other networks to chat on, you can find a list at <u>NetSplit.de</u> and other chat rooms can be found by searching on <u>SearchIRC.com</u>. When in a chat room, you can also type \U201c/search phrase\U201d and it will automatically open up <u>SearchIRC.com</u> with a search for your word or phrase.</p>";
	},
	{
		Title = "Push Notifications";
		Content = "<p>Push Notifications are a big part of the iPhone OS. Colloquy is the first IRC client on iPhone OS that supports Push Notifications! Due to how IRC works, Colloquy is a bit untraditional in how it has to generate Push Notifications. Instead of working directly with existing IRC server, you have to run a bouncer that will push notifications to your device. There are three ways to get push notifications:</p>\n<ol>\n\t<li>Using the Colloquy Bouncer, as detailed in the \U201cColloquy Bouncer\U201d section. This method will only work on Mac OS X Leopard or above.</li>\n\t<li>Using the ZNC bouncer with the Colloquy Push plugin. This will work on Mac OS X, Linux and Windows.</li>\n\t<li>Using a script for Irssi, that  will be released soon. This also works on Mac OS X, Linux and Windows.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Scripts and plugins for additional clients are planned. You can check for more scripts on the Colloquy website.</p>\n";
	},
	{
		Title = "Application Settings";
		Content = "<p>Colloquy has a large number of settings that you can use to customize how you interact with the application. Settings for Colloquy can be found in Settings on your device\U2019s home screen, under Colloquy.</p>";
